LAGOS – In the first trading day after Charismas, trading on the floor of The Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) closed southward yesterday when the two major indicators, the All Share Index and Market Capitalisation went down by 0.86 per cent each. The breakdown shows that the All Share Index (ASI) closed at 31,692.63 points after it went down by 274.38 basis points or 0.86 per cent as against 31,967.01 points recorded on Monday, while Market Capitalisation went down by N100.221 billion or 0.86 per cent to close at 11.576 trillion from N11.676 trillion it recorded in previous trading. Also, market turnover plunged by 49.78 per cent to N2.61 billion even as shares of Dangote Cement Plc dragged down NSE Industrial sector by 2.11 per cent to close at 1,248.57 points. Hence, the year-to-date loss of the NSE ASI increased 17.12 per cent. The downturn was impacted by losses recorded in medium and large capitalised stocks, amongst which are; Dangote Cement, Total Nigeria, UAC of Nigeria, Flour Mills Nigeria and FBN Holdings. Analysts at APT Securities and Funds Limited said that “we advise investors to monitor market movements and take advantage, as expectations for positive returns week on week (WoW) are still high amidst the marginal decline.” However, market breadth closed positive with 30 gainers against 16 losers. Conoil, Mutual Benefit Assurance and NPF Microfinance Bank recorded the highest price gain of 10 per cent, each to close at N23.10, 22 kobo and N1.65, per share, respectively.